title: Super 10 football rankings: Week 6 creates shake-up

Super 10 football rankings: Week 6 creates shake-up Chris Cuellar , ccuellar@dmreg.com 7:23 p.m. CDT October 4, 2015 Buy Photo Johnston and senior running back Grant Gossling (32) have joined the Super 10, but take on No. 1 Dowling Catholic in Week 7. (Photo: Brian Powers/The Register) Buy Photo 55 CONNECT 2 TWEET LINKEDIN COMMENT EMAIL MORE 
1. DOWLING CATHOLIC (5-0, 2-0) 
Last week: 1 
Just as it looked like ranked and rolling Sioux City East would put up a fight on Friday night, Dowling took over like it has so many times over the last three season. Four different players rushed for touchdowns, Michael Zachary added two more scores receiving and one on a punt return, and a 14-14 game finished 59-21. Another ranked challenge awaits against Johnston this week. 
2. BETTENDORF (6-0, 1-0) 
Last week: 2 
Senior Dax Emerson got his breakout game on Friday against Iowa City West, rushing for five touchdowns and 200 yards in a 48-20 win . The game was in hand early for Bettendorf, the runaway favorite in a middling Class 4A District 8, and the defense should be aggressive again in Week 7 against a North Scott team that managed just 10 points in two meetings last season. 
3. W.D.M. VALLEY (5-1, 2-0) 
Last week: 3 
The statistics look great in 4A-3 play, even if they don't mean much. Rocky Lombardi, Peyton Long and Will Rodruck all threw touchdown passes in a 69-0 win over Council Bluffs Abraham Lincoln, going 12-of-15 for 273 yards as a unit. Jevon Mason topped 100 yards on just seven carries and the defense forced four turnovers. The routs roll on. 4. CEDAR RAPIDS KENNEDY (6-0, 2-0) 
Last week: 6 
The Cougars are contenders through sheer force of will. Friday's 31-6 win at Linn-Mar was the fourth straight of allowing seven points or less. The offense isn't complicated: senior Tyler Dralle has taken 186 carries already — 63 more than any other player in 4A — and had 36 for 240 yards and two touchdowns in Week 6. 
5. FORT DODGE (6-0, 2-0) 
Last week: 4 
Indianola pushed the Dodgers down one spot by forcing them to play in the second half. Fort Dodge is still overpowering and unbeaten, but the cakewalk came to end in Week 6 as a typical 42-10 lead became a 49-36 game. It was a late, yet necessary wake-up call: "Our starters haven't played after halftime all year, and we looked like it," coach Matt Miller told the Register after the win . 6. PELLA (6-0, 4-0) 
Last week: 5 
Noah Clayberg scored five more touchdowns on just 15 touches and the Dutch defense held Carlisle to six points in 3A-7 play. Ho-hum. The district title is a formality for the top-ranked team in Class 3A, which faces Newton (0-6) and Saydel (1-5) in the next two weeks. 
7. CEDAR RAPIDS WASHINGTON (5-1, 2-0) 
Last week: 8 
Last year's 4A runner-ups are returning to form with a pair of excellent road wins to start district play. Four passing touchdowns, 125 rushing yards from Tavian Patrick and five forced turnovers paved the way to a 53-7 win at Ottumwa and only one winning team remains on the schedule. 
8. WEST DELAWARE (6-0, 4-0) 
Last week: 7 
Coy Roussell's quest for 2,000 rushing yards continues after Friday's requisite 196-yard, two-touchdown game, but the passing game might be even more important for the Hawks to stay unbeaten through October in 3A. Max Ridenour has thrown five touchdowns and no interceptions in the last two weeks. 
9. JOHNSTON (5-1, 2-0) 
Last week: NR 
Tough district dates means Johnston's stay in the Super 10 could be brief. The Dragons shut out Des Moines Roosevelt on Friday while getting seven rushing touchdowns from five different players, putting their depth and development in coach Brian Woodley's new offense on display.
